&lt;h2 id="1-design-the-main-algorithm">1. Design the main algorithm&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>We know that we are going to build a quiz with lots of questions, but let&amp;rsquo;s start small, and worry about just one question, as it seems likely
that the other questions we ask will have a lot of code in common. Let&amp;rsquo;s start with a basic algorithm.&lt;/p>
&lt;video controls>
&lt;source src="basicAlgorithm480.mp4" type="video/mp4">
Your browser does not support the video tag. Watch video &lt;a href="basicAlgorithm480.mp4">here&lt;/a>.
&lt;/video>
&lt;p>We want to ask the user a question, get their guess, and check it against the right answer. If they are correct, we praise them (and we&amp;rsquo;ll give them a point later). If they get it wrong, we&amp;rsquo;ll let them try again.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>We can test out our algorithm by starting at the Start and running our finger along the arrows to check that the behaviour is correct.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="2-some-code">2. Some code&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>Now let&amp;rsquo;s turn that into some code.&lt;/p>
&lt;video controls>
&lt;source src="basicCode.mp4" type="video/mp4">
Your browser does not support the video tag. Watch video &lt;a href="basicCode.mp4">here&lt;/a>.
&lt;/video>
&lt;p>We use &lt;code>print()&lt;/code> to talk to the user, and &lt;code>input()&lt;/code> to get responses back. So far our code doesn&amp;rsquo;t loop when the user guesses incorrectly.
Let&amp;rsquo;s add that now.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="3-code-with-retries">3. Code with retries&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>We can work out where to loop by working out the first and last bits of code that correspond with the parts of
the algorithm in the loop, and indent them. We can then write &lt;code>while True:&lt;/code> at the start of the loop. We then need to work out which decision
should end the loop, and put a &lt;code>break&lt;/code> there.&lt;/p>
&lt;video controls>
&lt;source src="codeWithLoop.mp4" type="video/mp4">
Your browser does not support the video tag. Watch video &lt;a href="codeWithLoop.mp4">here&lt;/a>.
&lt;/video>
&lt;p>We can slightly simplify our code here. Because we break out of the loop if the guess is correct,
we don&amp;rsquo;t need to put the case when the user is wrong inside an &lt;code>else&lt;/code> block.&lt;/p>
&lt;video controls>
&lt;source src="codeSimplifiedGuessElse.mp4" type="video/mp4">
Your browser does not support the video tag. Watch video &lt;a href="codeSimplifiedGuessElse.mp4">here&lt;/a>.
&lt;/video>
&lt;p>This works because if you get as far as the new line 7 we know that you guessed wrong (otherwise we&amp;rsquo;d have
broken out of the loop already). So we don&amp;rsquo;t need to check or clarify that.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="5-multiple-questions">5. Multiple questions&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>Let&amp;rsquo;s add a couple more questions. We can copy/paste the code we need to make more questions. So what do we need to copy?&lt;/p>
&lt;p>If you worked out it&amp;rsquo;s all of it, you&amp;rsquo;re right! We are going to extract this repeated part and make it into a function,
so we can write the code once and reuse it multiple times.&lt;/p>
&lt;video controls>
&lt;source src="codeWithFunction.mp4" type="video/mp4">
Your browser does not support the video tag. Watch video &lt;a href="codeWithFunction.mp4">here&lt;/a>.
&lt;/video></description></item><item><title>Assessment: 5: Game checkpoint</title><link>https://tmcdigitech.github.io/8/assessment/games/5-checkpoint/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://tmcdigitech.github.io/8/assessment/games/5-checkpoint/</guid><description/></item><item><title>Assessment: 6: Game project</title><link>https://tmcdigitech.github.io/8/assessment/games/6-project/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://tmcdigitech.github.io/8/assessment/games/6-project/</guid><description/></item></channel></rss>